{
  "query": "How do the effects of retaining crop residues on-site compare with incorporating plant material brought from elsewhere?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both retaining crop residues on-site and incorporating external plant material show positive effects on soil health, but with some distinct differences. \n\nFor on-site crop residue retention (Action 907): Studies found higher microbial biomass, reduced water runoff, increased water storage, and reduced soil erosion. Two randomized, replicated trials found higher soil organic carbon and nitrogen when residues were retained, with one trial showing this effect only when fertilizer was also applied. Higher yields were achieved when residues were retained, particularly when combined with fertilizer application and no-tillage.\n\nFor incorporating external plant material (Action 910): Studies found increased microbial biomass when crop remains and straw were added. Incorporating straw showed improved soil structure, with mixed effects on erosion depending on soil type - one study found reduced soil loss while another found mixed effects. All six studies measuring soil organic carbon found higher carbon levels when plant material was added, with one study finding higher carbon when straw was applied with NPK fertilizers. Higher barley yield and grain yields were found when external plant material was incorporated.\n\nExternal organic amendments like manures and composts (Action 911) showed additional benefits including higher microbial biomass and respiration, reduced nutrient loss, higher nitrogen levels, and higher crop yields. However, some organic processing wastes (Action 891) showed trade-offs - while improving soil structure and reducing soil loss, they also increased nutrient loss at high application rates.\n\nBoth approaches increase soil organic carbon and improve yields, but incorporating external materials may provide additional nutrient benefits, while residue retention focuses more on moisture conservation and erosion control with lower input costs.",
